  $lang['classes']['links']['content'] = '<p>You can always use the Web to search for information about many sites relating to the topic of this course or new concepts that you learn.</p><p>Remember it will be up to YOU to determine the validity of the sites you find. Some are excellent and can lead to lots of other sites; but some are very narrow in their understanding of Christian teachings etc, and will not be very helpful at all.</p><p>Here are some sites that might be helpful:</p><ol><li><b>United States Conference of Catholic Bishops:</b> '.vlc_external_link('http://www.usccb.org/', 'http://www.usccb.org/').'</li><li><b>Bible:</b> '.vlc_external_link('http://www.usccb.org/bible/', 'http://www.usccb.org/bible/').'</li><li><b>Bible (Alternate Website):</b> '.vlc_external_link('http://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG0839/_INDEX.HTM', 'http://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG0839/_INDEX.HTM').'</li><li><b>Catechism of the Catholic Church:</b> '.vlc_external_link('http://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG0015/_INDEX.HTM', 'http://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG0015/_INDEX.HTM').'</li><li><b>Catechism of the Catholic Church (Alternate Website):</b> '.vlc_external_link('http://www.usccb.org/catechism/text/', 'http://www.usccb.org/beliefs-and-teachings/what-we-believe/catechism/catechism-of-the-catholic-church/epub/index.cfm').'</li><li><b>Lonergan Research Institute:</b> '.vlc_external_link('http://www.lonergan-lri.ca/resources', 'http://www.lonergan-lri.ca/resources').'</li><li><b>Sacred Space - Jesuit:</b> '.vlc_external_link('http://sacredspace.ie/', 'http://sacredspace.ie/').'</li><li><b>Theology Library:</b> '.vlc_external_link('http://www.shc.edu/theolibrary/', 'http://www.shc.edu/theolibrary/').'</li><li><b>Canon Law:</b> '.vlc_external_link('http://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/_INDEX.HTM', 'http://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/_INDEX.HTM').'</li></ol>';
  $lang['classes']['keys'][47] = '<!-- (Key 1 - Placed next to the VLC - Mail Link) --><h2>Sending and Responding to VLC- Mail</h2><p>All communication for your course is through the built in mail system called VLC-Mail (See VLC-Mail link at the top of each page of the course).</p><ul><li>All course correspondence is in one place.</li><li>Check your VLC-Mail daily for messages from the course facilitator or from other students.</li><li>You will receive a VLC-Mail message for each new posting on the discussion boards for easy review and access.</li><li>You can send a message to your facilitator or to another student from VLC-Mail. Click on their name and send your message.</li><li>You can send a VLC-Mail message to the entire class by clicking on the box select all users.</li><li>On the main website page is a menu with a Contact Us bar. From here you can contact your course facilitator, VLCFF Technical Support Coordinator (Richard Drabik), or the VLCFF Director (Sr. Angela Ann Zukowski).</li></ul>';
  $lang['classes']['keys'][48] = '<!-- (Key 2 - This key goes into session #1 - it goes before the 1st discussion board) --><h2>Community of Learners</h2><p>The VLCFF is an interactive e-learning experience grounded on forming a community of learners. Therefore, keep the following guidelines in mind:</p><ul><li>The Discussion Boards are the heart of the e-learning experience.</li><li>Consistent, active participation on the Discussion Boards each week is required to successfully complete the course. There are no exceptions.</li><li>The Discussion Board is the space for demonstrating your understanding and integration of the session content and session objectives.</li><li>A community of learners is formed when each student commits to being an active and engaged participant on each Discussion Board.</li><li>You are required to post three (3) times on each Discussion Board. First, post your insights and reflections, then return to post responses to other students\' postings.</li><li>Students need to keep a balance between talking about feelings and experiences versus immersing themselves in critical reading, reflection and communication related to the focus questions on the Discussion Boards.</li><li>The Discussion Board is not the space for advocating a particular perspective in a manipulative or domineering manner. See the upcoming Key 4 on netiquette.</li></ul>';
  $lang['classes']['keys'][49] = '<!-- (Key 3 - Goes into Session #1 before the 1st reading) --><h2>Critical Reading and Reflection Skills</h2><p>Reading is a very personalized activity. How you read for your online course depends a lot on your background and your familiarity with the course subject. However, there are a few general strategies for increasing your comprehension and reading rate that work for almost any online student. These strategies include the following:</p><ul><li>Preview your reading material by looking over the chapter or article.</li><li>Set a time limit for completing your reading assignment and read to meet that goal.</li><li>Use an underlining system as a way to stay focused.</li><li>Read an entire section before you stop reading.</li><li>Take reading notes at the end of each section.</li><li>Review your notes before you start another section.</li><li>The question(s) on the Discussion Boards are related to the readings. You are asked to share your insights from the readings on the Discussion Boards, not to give back word for word what is in the book. Everyone has already read it. By critically thinking about the readings, you integrate them into your own life establishing a rich ground for further readings along the way.</li></ul><h2>How to Sharpen Your Critical Reading Strategies</h2><ul><li>Be aware of your previous knowledge and value assumptions on the topic.</li><li>Be alert to the author\'s point of view, message, arguments, evidence and conclusions.</li><li>Be open to what the author is expressing as you explore new insights and knowledge.</li><li>Be sensitive to how the author\'s insights connect with Church teaching, and how they offer deeper perspectives or commentary.</li><li>Reflect on the author\'s use of evidence to support their conclusions.</li><li>Be conscious of your own response or reaction to the reading.</li></ul><h2>Reader\'s Reaction to the Reading</h2><ul><li>What have I learned after reading this chapter or article?</li><li>How might I express what I learned in my own words?</li><li>How does the reading connect with the objectives of the course and the objectives of this session?</li><li>What would I like to learn more about?</li></ul>';
  $lang['classes']['keys'][50] = '<!-- (Key 4 - This goes before the 1st discussion board in Session #2) --><h2>Netiquette--A Culture of Respect</h2><p>Netiquette refers to the proper etiquette when communicating in an online setting. The Internet introduces a new way of communicating that requires that we nurture skills for respectful e-conversations. We realize that students come from diverse religious, spiritual and cultural backgrounds. These experiences enrich, enlighten and sometimes challenge us as we journey together online. Therefore, practice cultivating a culture of respect within your course by adhering to the following guidelines:</p><ul><li>Be open to the insights of others who may have opinions that differ from your own.</li><li>Be able to differentiate official Church teaching from theological opinions/insights and sound scriptural foundations as they each have a place within our learning experience.</li><li>Be sensitive to diverse backgrounds and ways of expression.</li><li>Be careful with words, tones, attitudes and expressions online.</li><li>Be careful not to offend others when expressing an opposing opinion or belief.</li><li>Hold sacred the dignity of each student online.</li><li>If there is a serious theological problem, your facilitator will address the issue one-on-one with the student, not necessarily within the public online forum.</li></ul>';
  $lang['classes']['keys'][51] = '<!-- (Key 5 - This key goes into session 3 before the first reading) --><h2>The Process of Theological Reflection for Understanding and Integration</h2><ul><li>Read the statement on <strong>Theological Reflection</strong> below.</li><li>Read with an <strong>open mind.</strong></li><li>Identify the <strong>key elements or position</strong> presented by the author.</li><li>Take <strong>quality time</strong> to critically reflect, discern and rephrase in your own words what the author is trying to communicate.</li><li><strong>Pray</strong> about the ideas that are emerging in your consciousness.</li><li><strong>Reflect</strong> on how this new learning relates to your current understanding, or insights you discovered from other authors.</li><li>To ensure clear communication, carefully <strong>organize</strong> your thoughts before posting them on the Discussion Boards.</li></ul><h3>Theological Reflection</h3><p>Please read these guidelines. This is essential for your practice of theological reflection during our time together. It is critical for effectively participating in the course Discussion Boards and completing the course.</p><p>One of the overarching goals of this program is to help you to become better able to discern what God is saying both to you as an individual and to our Church in and through these turbulent times. To accomplish this requires that we place our life experiences in dialogue with our Christian heritage. It means that we enter into a conversation with those who have gone before us, that we make their questions in some sense our questions. In this conversation we may find ourselves transformed by new perspectives on our own experiences and by a deeper appreciation of our tradition.</p><p>This conversation requires that we employ a reflective process known as theological reflection. More than teaching theology, it is a process that teaches us to think theologically. Using theological reflection, we will not merely learn about the story of the Church, but we will dialogue with the story, ask questions of the story, allow the story to ask questions of us, enter into relationship with it and, in some sense, re-write it for our lifetimes. We will treat the tradition of our Church as a source of wisdom for us while recognizing that, in order to make it useful to us, we need to place this wisdom within the context of our lives today.</p><p>Through this process we will be asked to examine our experiences carefully, extracting from them deeper meaning, images and voices. We will look to our tradition through the story of our Church to uncover that meaning. And we will place these two, our experience and the tradition, in dialogue with one another in order to gain deeper insights into both. Out of this dialogue will emerge some new connections with God\'s presence and purposes for us. We hope to discover new directions, new visions of the future, new ways to live together in response to God\'s ever-present call.</p><p>Therefore, the Discussion Boards are a critical dimension for engaging in theological reflection during our time together. These are essential, not an option, for completing the course.</p><p>How to practice and develop the skill of theological reflection on our Discussion Boards:</p><ul><li>First, you must both prayerfully and critically read and reflect on the readings for each session as they are assigned for the week.</li><li>Second, ask yourself these questions: What is the author saying? How does it relate to your faith journey or previous faith studies (Scripture or Catholic traditions)? How does it relate to your life experience? Is there any connection or interpretation for your community and culture where you live? What might God be saying to you as you engage in theological reflection today?</li><li>Third, what new insights do you glean from these reflections on the readings?</li><li>Fourth, communicate -- share (post) your insights and reflections as related to the readings -- on each session\'s Discussion Boards. Be sure that your posting is connected with the theme of the session. Write 2-3 paragraphs (4-6 sentences per paragraph) for your posting response. You can write more but do not write less.</li><li>Fifth, carefully read and reflect upon the comments and insights offered by our class members on the Discussion Boards. Do their insights affirm, invite or challenge your own understanding of the aim of this particular session? Post your additional reflections two (2) more times during the week. This is where our "cyber community of faith" is nurtured and formed. A good idea is to check in one last time the day before the session ends to contribute to the discussion.</li><li>Sixth, it is imperative to remember that the Discussion Boards are to be "grounded" in theological reflection -- for "depth listening and learning" from the Spirit and our cyber-faith community.</li></ul>';
  $lang['classes']['keys'][52] = '<!-- (Key 6 - This goes into Session #5 or the last seminar session) --><h2>Answers to Questions Concerning Certificate Upon Completing the Course</h2><p>The following process is followed once the course is closed:</p><ul><li>The course facilitator informs each student whether they have successfully completed the course.</li><li>The course facilitator sends the list of names of students who have successfully completed the course to our VLCFF staff.</li><li>Certificates are then prepared by the VLCFF staff.</li><li>If your diocese is a VLCFF Partner, the certificate is sent to your diocesan representative to be co-signed. The diocese then sends the certificate directly to you.</li><li>If your diocese is not a VLCFF Partner, the certificate is sent directly to you with Sr. Angela Ann Zukowski\'s (Director) signature.</li></ul><p>This final process normally takes 3-5 weeks to complete.</p>';
  $lang['classes']['evaluation']['intro'] = '[p]We are interested in having your feedback on your experience with the online course. We realize that we have a rich diversity of persons engaged in our courses. We want to be able to learn from your experience for enhancing VLCFF.[/p][p]Please fill in the following information. Thank you for taking the time to respond to our questionnaire. Our prayers and best wishes are extended to you. We look forward to having you join us on another course.[/p]';
  $lang['classes']['evaluation']['questions'][] = 'What is your general attitude of online courses after completing this course?';
  $lang['classes']['evaluation']['questions'][] = 'What were the advantages to an online course especially in relationship to other courses you have taken?';
  $lang['classes']['evaluation']['questions'][] = 'What was your significant learning experience with the online course?';
